<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-415-624  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 415 624.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  June 21 1989 n1466 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fibre optics - just hot air?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Marsh, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber optics promises great weight, performance, cost,electromagnetic interference immunity, and security advantages,but engineers and systems designers have been slow to utilizethose advantages despite the availability of viable fiber opticsproducts.andP;  The major impediments to acceptance of fiber opticsinclude engineers who base their design solutions on familiar wiretechnology, the computer industry's concern about adapting fiberoptics to existing systems, little promotion of the use of fiberoptics by such organizations as NATO, and the problems involved insplicing or terminating fiber optic cables.andP;  Fiber optic productsmanufacturers are offering a variety of advanced productssolutions, including Litton Veam's SMA-type expanded beamconnector, 3M's single and multimode connector, and ITT Cannon'sfast fiber fusing process.andP;  Mil-spec connectors are brieflydiscussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsOptoelectronic DevicesConnectorsSystem DesignProduct DevelopmentImpact AnalysisManufacturers.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Conventional fiber optic termination methods. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>